                <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" n="1">
                    <ab>
                        <seg type="context"  resp="strabo" n="1"><title>Strab. 12, 3, 20:</title>
                            The <persName key="demetriosskepsis" nymRef="Δημήτριος ὁ Σκήψιος">scholar
                        from Scepsis</persName> also considers to change the name from <placeName
                        type="ethnic" nymRef="Ἄλυβες" ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/554184"
                            >“Alybes”</placeName> to <placeName type="ethnic" nymRef="Χάλυβες"
                        >“Chalybes”</placeName>, but, as he does not take into account what would
                    follow from this or what would be in agreement with it, - in particular why the
                    poet would have called the <placeName type="ethnic" nymRef="Χάλυβες"
                        >Chalybes</placeName>
                    <placeName type="ethnic" nymRef="Ἁλιζῶνες">Halizones</placeName> -, he rejects
                    this opinion (...)</seg>
                        
                        <seg type="context"  resp="strabo" n="2"><title>Strab. 12, 3, 22:</title>
                            The <persName key="demetriosskepsis" nymRef="Δημήτριος ὁ Σκήψιος">scholar
                        from Scepsis</persName>, accepting apparently neither <persName
                        key="Ephorus" nymRef="Ἔφορος">this scholar</persName>'s opinion nor the one
                    from those supposing that the <placeName type="ethnic" nymRef="Ἁλιζῶνες"
                        >Halizones</placeName> come from near <placeName type="city" key="pallene"
                        nymRef="Παλλήνην" ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/491682"
                        >Pallene</placeName> (whom I mention in the parts on <placeName
                        type="region" key="macedonia" nymRef="Μακεδονία"
                        ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/491656">Macedonia</placeName>), is
                    likewise at lost to understand how someone could consider that an allied force
                    could have been sent to the <placeName type="ethnic" nymRef="Τρῶες"
                        >Trojans</placeName> from among the nomads living beyond the <placeName
                        type="region" key="borysthenes" nymRef="Βορυσθένης"
                        ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/828250">Borysthenes</placeName>. He,
                    however, fully approves of the opinions defended by <persName
                        key="hecataeusmiletus" nymRef="Ἑκαταῖος ὁ Μιλήσιος"><name>Hecataeus</name>
                        <nameLink>of</nameLink>
                        <name>Miletus</name></persName>, by <persName key="menecrateselea"
                        nymRef="Μενεκράτης ὁ Ἐλαΐτης">Menecrates <nameLink>from</nameLink>
                        <name>Elaea</name></persName>, one among the disciples of <persName
                        key="xenocrates" nymRef="Ξενοκράτης"><name>Xenocrates</name></persName>, and
                    by <persName key="palaephatus" nymRef="Παλαίφατος"
                        ><name>Palaephatus</name></persName>. Among these men, the <persName
                        key="hecataeusmiletus" nymRef="Ἑκαταῖος ὁ Μιλήσιος">first</persName> says in
                    his <title>Circuit of the Earth</title>:
                        </seg> 
                            
                        <seg type="fragment" resp="hecataeus" n="3">
                            <quote>Then comes
                            the city of <placeName type="city" key="alazia" nymRef="Ἀλαζία"
                                >Alazia</placeName>; the river <geogName type="river" key="odryses"
                                nymRef="Ὀδρύσσης" ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/511340"
                                >Odrysses</geogName>, flowing from lake <geogName type="lake"
                                key="daskylitis" nymRef="Δασκυλίτις"
                                ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/511224">Dascylitis</geogName>
                            eastwards through the <geogName type="plain" key="mygdonia"
                                nymRef="Μυγδονία" ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/511325"
                                >Mygdonian plain</geogName>, empties into the river <geogName
                                type="river" key="rhydacus" nymRef="Ῥύνδακος"
                                ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/511401"
                            >Rhyndacus</geogName>.</quote>
                        </seg>
                        
                        <seg type="context" resp="strabo" n="4">
                            He says that <placeName type="city"
                        key="alazia" nymRef="Ἀλαζία">Alazia</placeName> is now deserted, but that
                    many villages of the <placeName type="ethnic" nymRef="Ἁλιζῶνες"
                        >Alazones</placeName>, through whose territory the <geogName type="river"
                        key="odryses" nymRef="Ὀδρύσσης" ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/511340"
                        >Odrysses</geogName> flows, are inhabited; that <persName type="divine"
                        key="apollo" nymRef="Ἀπόλλων"><name>Apollo</name></persName> was honoured
                    there in a particularly intensive way, especially along the border with the
                        <placeName type="ethnic" key="cyzicus" nymRef="Κύζικος"
                        ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/511218">Cyziceni</placeName>. <persName
                        key="menecrateselea" nymRef="Μενεκράτης ὁ Ἐλαΐτης"
                        ><name>Menecrates</name></persName>, in his <title>Circuit of the
                        Hellespont</title>,
                        </seg> 
                        
                        <seg type="fragment" resp="menecrates" n="5">
                            <quote>says thatabove the area belonging
                        to <placeName type="region" key="myrleia" nymRef="Μύρλεια"
                            ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/511194">Myrleia</placeName>, lies a
                        continous mountainous plateau, that is inhabited by the tribe of the
                            <placeName type="ethnic" nymRef="Ἁλιζῶνες">Halizones</placeName>. He
                        claims that it has to be written with two lambda, but that the poet spells
                        it with one because of the meter.</quote>
                        </seg>
                        
                        <seg type="context" resp="strabo" n="6">
                            <persName key="palaephatus" nymRef="Παλαίφατος"><name>Palaephatus</name></persName>, finally, says
                        </seg>
                        
                        <seg type="fragment" resp="palaephatus" n="7">
                        that <persName key="odius" nymRef="Ὄδιος"><name>Odios</name></persName> and
                            <persName key="epistrophus" nymRef="Ἐπίστροφος"
                            ><name>Epistrophos</name></persName> started their expedition from the
                            <placeName type="ethnic" nymRef="Ἁλιζῶνες">Alazones</placeName> who
                            dwelt in <placeName corresp="alybe" nymRef="Ἀλόπη">Alope</placeName>, which
                        is now <placeName type="city" key="zeleia" nymRef="Ζέλεια"
                            ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/511461">Zeleia</placeName>.
                        </seg>
                        
                
                <seg type="context" resp="strabo" n="8">
                    Nonetheless, <persName key="demetriosskepsis" nymRef="Δημήτριος ὁ Σκήψιος"
                        >Demetrios</persName> pretends that those who located the <placeName
                        type="ethnic" key="amazons" nymRef="Ἀμαζῶνες">Amazons</placeName> near
                        <placeName type="city" key="pygela" nymRef="Πύγελα"
                        ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/599887/pygela">Pygela</placeName>,
                    between <placeName type="city" key="ephesus" nymRef="Ἔφεσος"
                        ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/599612">Ephesus</placeName>, <placeName
                        type="city" key="magnesiamaeander" nymRef="Μαγνησία"
                        ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/599778">Magnesia</placeName> and
                        <placeName type="city" key="priene" nymRef="Πριήνη"
                        ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/599905">Priene</placeName>, talk
                    nonsense, because the formula <quote>from far away</quote> does not fit this
                    place. How much more it is unfitting for the region near <placeName type="city"
                        key="mysia" nymRef="Μυσία" ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/550759"
                        >Mysia</placeName> and <placeName type="city" key="teuthrania"
                        nymRef="Τευθρανία" ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/550916"
                        >Teuthrania</placeName>!</seg>
                        
                        <seg type="context" resp="strabo" n="9"><title>Strab. 12, 3, 23:</title> 
                            But, by <persName type="divine" key="zeus" nymRef="Ζεύς"><name>Zeus</name></persName>, 
                            he says that it is necessary to understand
                    that some formula have been added while being used in an improper sense, as for
                    instance <ref target="urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001:2.863">(Il. 2. 863)</ref> <quote>far from <placeName type="city" key="askania" nymRef="Ἀσκανία"
                            ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/511165">Ascania</placeName></quote> and 
                            <ref target="urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002:18.5">(Od. 18.5)</ref> <quote>he has the name of <persName key="arnaeus"
                            nymRef="Αρναῖος"><name>Arnaeus</name></persName>; the august mother gave
                                it</quote> and <ref target="urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002:21.6">(Od. 21.6)</ref> <quote>(<persName key="penelope" nymRef="Πηνελόπη"
                                ><name>Penelope</name></persName>) took the nicely bent key with her
                        strong hand</quote>. Let’s accept this too. But one has not to
                    accept the elements with which <persName key="demetriosskepsis"
                        nymRef="Δημήτριος ὁ Σκήψιος">Demetrios</persName>, after having given them
                    all his attention, is not able to give a convincing responds to those who
                    maintain that one should hear the line <quote><ref target="urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001:2.857">far away from the
                                <placeName type="city" key="calybe" nymRef="Χαλύβη"
                                >Chalybe</placeName></ref></quote>. For, albeit he makes the
                    concession that it is possible that silver-mines may have existed in the country
                    of the <placeName type="ethnic" nymRef="Χάλυβες">Chalybes</placeName>, even if
                    they do not exist anymore today, he does, however, not agree that they were
                    famous and worthy of notice like the iron-mines (...)
                    What then, if the silver-mines did not reach fame in the Heroic time but in
                        <persName key="homer" nymRef="Ὅμηρος"><name>Homer</name></persName>’s one?
                    Could one blame the assertion of the <persName key="homer" nymRef="Ὅμηρος"
                            ><name>poet</name></persName>? How then did the fame come to the
                        <persName key="homer" nymRef="Ὅμηρος"><name>poet</name></persName>'s ears?
                    And how did the fame of the copper-mines of <placeName type="city" key="temesa"
                        nymRef="Τεμέση">Temesa</placeName> in <placeName type="region" key="italy"
                        nymRef="Ἰταλία" ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/1052"
                        >Italy</placeName> reach him? (Od. 1.184) (...)
                        </seg>
                        
                        <seg type="testimonium" resp="strabo" n="10"><title>[T8]</title> 
                            But, he does not even agree with
                        those whose opinion he is defending. For, while describing the region around
                            <placeName type="city" key="skepsis" nymRef="Σκῆψις"
                            ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/550890">Scepsis</placeName>, his
                        own hometown, he mentions near <placeName type="city" key="skepsis"
                            nymRef="Σκῆψις" ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/550890"
                            >Scepsis</placeName> and the <geogName type="river" key="aesepus"
                            nymRef="Αἴσηπος" ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/511141"
                            >Aesepos</geogName>, the village <placeName type="city" key="ainea"
                            nymRef="Αἰνέα" ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/554179"
                            >Ainea</placeName>, <placeName type="city" key="argyria"
                            nymRef="Ἀργυρία" ref="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/550451"
                            >Argyria</placeName> and <placeName type="city" key="alazonion"
                            nymRef="Ἀλαζόνιον">Alazonion</placeName> (...) 
                            <persName key="hecataeusmiletus" nymRef="Ἑκαταῖος ὁ Μιλήσιος"
                            ><name>Hecataeus</name></persName>(...)
                        </seg>
                    </ab>
            </div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <p>1) In this passage Biraschi does sometimes not follow Radt's edition.</p>
                <p>2) By mistake Biraschi refers to the end of the fragment as being T9. It is,
                    however, T8.</p>
            </div>

